{"id":"2303.06301","submitter":"Hodaka Yamaji","authors":"Hodaka Yamaji","title":"On the Number of Maximal Cliques in Two-Dimensional Random Geometric\n  Graphs: Euclidean and Hyperbolic","comments":"22 pages, 6 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cs.DM","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Maximal clique enumeration appears in various real-world networks, such as\nsocial networks and protein-protein interaction networks for different\napplications. For general graph inputs, the number of maximal cliques can be up\nto $3^{|V|/3}$. However, many previous works suggest that the number is much\nsmaller than that on real-world networks, and polynomial-delay algorithms\nenable us to enumerate them in a realistic-time span. To bridge the gap between\nthe worst case and practice, we consider the number of maximal cliques in two\npopular models of real-world networks: Euclidean random geometric graphs and\nhyperbolic random graphs. We show that the number of maximal cliques on\nEuclidean random geometric graphs is lower and upper bounded by\n$\\exp(\\Omega(|V|^{1/3}))$ and $\\exp(O(|V|^{1/3+\\epsilon}))$ with high\nprobability for any $\\epsilon > 0$. For a hyperbolic random graph, we give the\nbounds of $\\exp(\\Omega(|V|^{(3-\\gamma)/6}))$ and\n$\\exp(O(|V|^{(3-\\gamma+\\epsilon)/6)}))$ where $\\gamma$ is the power-law degree\nexponent between 2 and 3.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sat, 11 Mar 2023 04:19:11 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-03-14"}
