{"id":"2303.06406","submitter":"Tam\\'as Csern\\'ak","authors":"Tam\\'as Csern\\'ak","title":"Colorings of Graph Products","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.CO","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/4.0/","abstract":"  The product $G\\times H$ of two graphs is {\\em trivially colorable} iff any\n$\\chi(G\\times H)$-coloring of $G\\times H$ is induced by a coloring of a factor.\nA finite graph $G$ is said to be {\\em tight} if any two $\\chi(G)$-colorings of\n$G$ differ in at least two points. Greenwell and Lov\\'asz proved that if $G$ is\nconnected and tight with $\\chi(G)\\ge 3$, then $G\\times K_{\\chi(G)}$ is\ntrivially colorable. Strengthening their result, we prove that $G\\times H$ is\ntrivially colorable provided $\\chi(G)=\\chi(H)\\ge 3$, $G$ is connected and\ntight, and $H$ is {\\em weakly cliqued}, i.e. every vertex of $H$ is in a clique\nof size $\\chi(H)$. Using this theorem we show that every connected weakly\ncliqued graph with $\\chi(G)\\ge 3$ is {\\em trivially power-colorable}, i.e.\nevery finite power of $G^n$ is trivially colorable. We also characterize the\ntrivially power-colorable cographs. Finally, we describe the colorings of\ninfinite powers of trivially power-colorable graphs.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sat, 11 Mar 2023 13:17:10 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-03-14"}
